      "sql": "SELECT dept, COUNT(*) AS cnt\nFROM employees\nGROUP BY dept\nHAVING COUNT(*) > (\n  SELECT AVG(cnt)\n  FROM (\n    SELECT COUNT(*) AS cnt\n    FROM employees\n    GROUP BY dept\n  )\n)\nORDER BY cnt DESC, dept;",
      "explanation": "**Strategy:** avoid the CTE entirely by embedding both aggregations inside a single `HAVING` clause. The outer query groups by department; the threshold is computed on the fly via a nested subquery.\n\n**Step 1 ÔÇö outer GROUP BY.** `SELECT dept, COUNT(*) AS cnt FROM employees GROUP BY dept` is identical to the first step in the CTE approach ÔÇö one row per department with its size.\n\n**Step 2 ÔÇö nested subquery for the average.** Inside `HAVING`, the condition is `COUNT(*) > (SELECT AVG(cnt) FROM (SELECT COUNT(*) AS cnt FROM employees GROUP BY dept))`. The inner-most subquery re-aggregates `employees` to get every department's count, and the middle `AVG(...)` averages those counts. SQLite evaluates this scalar once and compares it against each department's `COUNT(*)`.\n\n**Step 3 ÔÇö why this works without a CTE.** The derived table `(SELECT COUNT(*) ... GROUP BY dept)` plays the same role as the `counts` CTE ÔÇö it materialises the per-department counts so `AVG` can operate on them. SQLite allows a subquery in `FROM` (a derived table), making the CTE unnecessary here.\n\n**Step 4 ÔÇö order.** Same `ORDER BY cnt DESC, dept` produces the same result."
