      "sql": "SELECT customer, ROUND(cust_avg, 2) AS cust_avg\nFROM (\n  SELECT customer,\n         AVG(amount) OVER (PARTITION BY customer) AS cust_avg,\n         AVG(amount) OVER ()                      AS global_avg\n  FROM orders\n)\nGROUP BY customer\nHAVING cust_avg > global_avg\nORDER BY cust_avg DESC;",
      "explanation": "### Goal\nUse **window functions** to compute both the per-customer average and the global average as extra columns on every row, then filter and deduplicate with `GROUP BY ÔÇŽ HAVING`.\n\n### Why window functions\nA window function like `AVG(amount) OVER (PARTITION BY customer)` computes an aggregate but does **not** collapse rows ÔÇö each order row keeps its own identity and also carries the group aggregate. This lets both averages travel alongside every row so we can compare them without a join or subquery.\n\n### Walking the query\n\n**1. Inner SELECT with two window functions:**\n- `AVG(amount) OVER (PARTITION BY customer)` ÔÇö for each row, the average of all orders by the same customer. Every row in a group gets the same value.\n- `AVG(amount) OVER ()` ÔÇö the window is the entire table (empty `OVER ()`), so every row gets the same global average Ôëł 194.29.\n\nAfter this step we have 7 rows, each carrying `cust_avg` and `global_avg`.\n\n**2. Outer `GROUP BY customer`** ÔÇö collapses each customer's multiple rows into one (they all share the same `cust_avg` and `global_avg`, so `MIN`/`MAX`/`HAVING` on these are consistent).\n\n**3. `HAVING cust_avg > global_avg`** ÔÇö the window values are plain column references here, so the comparison is straightforward. Ava (100) and Cyd (50) are filtered out.\n\n**4. `SELECT customer, ROUND(cust_avg, 2) ÔÇŽ ORDER BY cust_avg DESC`** ÔÇö final projection and sort.\n\n### What makes it distinct\nNo subquery for the global average, no CTE, no cross-join. Both aggregates are injected as window columns and exist side-by-side on every row, demonstrating how window functions can replace a self-join or a CTE when you need two different grain aggregates simultaneously."
