      "name": "Bottom-up recursive CTE (traverse toward root)",
      "sql": "WITH RECURSIVE chain(orig_name, cur_manager_id, path) AS (\n  SELECT name, manager_id, name FROM employees\n  UNION ALL\n  SELECT c.orig_name, e.manager_id, e.name || ' > ' || c.path\n  FROM chain c\n  JOIN employees e ON e.id = c.cur_manager_id\n)\nSELECT orig_name AS name, path\nFROM chain\nWHERE cur_manager_id IS NULL\nORDER BY path;",
      "explanation": "### Goal\nSame breadcrumb `path` result, but this time we **start at every employee and walk up toward the root**, prepending each ancestor's name as we go.\n\n### Walking the query\n\n**1. The anchor ÔÇö `SELECT name, manager_id, name FROM employees`** ÔÇö seeds one row per employee. Each employee starts a separate traversal with `path = name` (just their own name) and `cur_manager_id` pointing at their direct manager.\n\n**2. The recursive member** ÔÇö\n```\nSELECT c.orig_name, e.manager_id, e.name || ' > ' || c.path\nFROM chain c\nJOIN employees e ON e.id = c.cur_manager_id\n```\nFor any in-progress traversal that hasn't yet reached the root, we join on the manager's `id`, then **prepend** the manager's name: `e.name || ' > ' || c.path`. We also carry the manager's own `manager_id` forward so the next iteration can keep climbing. `orig_name` is frozen from the anchor ÔÇö it always identifies which employee this traversal belongs to.\n\n- Frank's traversal: `'Frank'` Ôćĺ `'Dan > Frank'` Ôćĺ `'Bob > Dan > Frank'` Ôćĺ `'Alice > Bob > Dan > Frank'`\n\nTermination: the recursion naturally stops when `cur_manager_id IS NULL` (there is no manager to join against).\n\n**3. `WHERE cur_manager_id IS NULL`** ÔÇö filters to rows that have reached the root and thus contain the complete path. Intermediate states (partial paths) are discarded.\n\n**4. `SELECT orig_name AS name, path ÔÇŽ ORDER BY path`** ÔÇö aliases the frozen original name back to `name` to match the expected output.\n\n### Contrast with the top-down approach\nThe top-down CTE visits each node exactly once; the bottom-up CTE runs one independent traversal per employee. For a tree with N nodes and max depth D, the bottom-up approach does O(N ├Ś D) work vs. O(N) for the top-down. The top-down approach is more efficient; the bottom-up is a useful mental model for understanding ancestor paths."
