      "sql": "SELECT DISTINCT l.customer\nFROM last_year l\nLEFT JOIN this_year t ON l.customer = t.customer\nWHERE t.customer IS NULL\nORDER BY l.customer;",
      "explanation": "1. A `LEFT JOIN` keeps every `last_year` row and attaches any matching `this_year` row; unmatched rows get `NULL` on the right side.\n2. `WHERE t.customer IS NULL` filters to only those unmatched rows ÔÇö i.e., customers who did **not** buy this year.\n3. `SELECT DISTINCT` is essential here: without it, a customer with multiple `last_year` rows (like Bea's duplicate) would appear multiple times in the output. The trap version omits `DISTINCT` and produces wrong results.\n4. The final result is Ada, Dev ÔÇö the same set difference as `EXCEPT`, but expressed as a join operation."
