      "name": "position scan via numbers CTE",
      "sql": "WITH RECURSIVE nums(n) AS (\n  SELECT 1\n  UNION ALL\n  SELECT n + 1 FROM nums WHERE n < 1000\n)\nSELECT r.id, r.tags,\n       1 + SUM(CASE WHEN substr(r.tags, n.n, 1) = ',' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) AS item_count\nFROM rows_tags r\nJOIN nums n ON n.n <= length(r.tags)\nGROUP BY r.id, r.tags\nORDER BY r.id;",
      "explanation": "1. The recursive `nums` CTE generates a sequence of integers 1, 2, ÔÇŽ 1000 ÔÇö one row per possible character position.\n2. Each source row is cross-joined against only those positions that fall within its `tags` string (`n <= length(tags)`).\n3. `CASE WHEN substr(tags, n, 1) = ','` inspects the character at each position; `SUM(...)` counts how many positions are commas.\n4. Adding `1` converts the comma count to an item count, and `GROUP BY` collapses back to one row per source row.\n5. The 1000-position ceiling comfortably covers any realistic tag string; increase it if extremely long strings are expected."
