  "count-star-vs-count-col": [
    {
      "name": "FILTER clause",
      "sql": "SELECT COUNT(*) AS total_rows,\n       COUNT(*) FILTER (WHERE score IS NOT NULL) AS rated_rows,\n       ROUND(AVG(score) FILTER (WHERE score IS NOT NULL), 2) AS avg_score\nFROM reviews;",
      "explanation": "The `FILTER (WHERE ...)` clause is an SQL standard extension that restricts which rows an aggregate function processes, without affecting `FROM` or `WHERE`. Here:\n- `COUNT(*) FILTER (WHERE score IS NOT NULL)` counts only rows where `score` is not NULL ÔÇö equivalent to `COUNT(score)` but expressed as an explicit row filter on `COUNT(*)`.\n- `AVG(score) FILTER (WHERE score IS NOT NULL)` averages only non-NULL scores; while `AVG` already ignores NULLs, the FILTER makes the intent explicit and generalises to other aggregates.\n- This approach teaches that FILTER is a composable per-aggregate filter, useful when you need multiple aggregates with different conditions in a single pass."
    },
    {
      "name": "CASE-based counting",
      "sql": "SELECT COUNT(*) AS total_rows,\n       SUM(CASE WHEN score IS NOT NULL THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) AS rated_rows,\n       ROUND(\n         SUM(CASE WHEN score IS NOT NULL THEN score ELSE 0 END) * 1.0\n         / NULLIF(SUM(CASE WHEN score IS NOT NULL THEN 1 ELSE 0 END), 0),\n         2\n       ) AS avg_score\nFROM reviews;",
      "explanation": "Uses `CASE` expressions inside aggregate functions to handle NULLs explicitly:\n- `SUM(CASE WHEN score IS NOT NULL THEN 1 ELSE 0 END)` counts non-NULL rows by mapping each to 1 or 0 and summing ÔÇö equivalent to `COUNT(score)`.\n- The average is computed manually: sum of non-NULL scores divided by count of non-NULL rows. `NULLIF(..., 0)` guards against division by zero when all scores are NULL, returning NULL in that case (matching what `AVG` returns on an all-NULL set).\n- This strategy predates the `FILTER` clause and works on databases that do not support it; it also generalises to weighted sums and other conditional aggregations."
    }
  ],
  "coworker-pairs-in-same-department": [
    {
      "name": "Correlated subquery with EXISTS",
      "sql": "SELECT a.name AS employee_a, b.name AS employee_b, a.dept AS dept\nFROM employees a\nJOIN employees b ON a.name < b.name\nWHERE EXISTS (\n  SELECT 1\n  FROM employees c\n  WHERE c.id = a.id AND c.dept = b.dept\n)\nORDER BY dept, employee_a, employee_b;",
      "explanation": "**Step 1 ÔÇö generate candidate pairs differently.** Rather than filtering the same-department constraint inside the join, `employees a JOIN employees b ON a.name < b.name` first generates all pairs of employees (across any department) where the first name sorts before the second. This handles deduplication (no A-B and B-A, no self-pairs) at the join stage.\n\n**Step 2 ÔÇö use EXISTS to check the shared department.** For each candidate pair `(a, b)`, the correlated `EXISTS` subquery asks: is there a row in `employees` where the employee has `a`'s id *and* `b`'s department? If so, `a` and `b` are in the same department and the pair qualifies. The correlated subquery re-enters the table to verify the department match rather than doing it inline in the join condition.\n\n**Step 3 ÔÇö why this is a different strategy.** The separation of concerns is the key difference: the join builds the deduplicated universe of all employee pairs, and the WHERE/EXISTS clause acts as an independent filter that checks the department property. This mirrors the correlated-subquery pattern you'd use for more complex membership checks (e.g., \"has this pair shared any project?\").\n\n**Step 4 ÔÇö result is identical.** The three strategies (name <, id <, and EXISTS) all produce the same rows; the final `ORDER BY` produces the same deterministic order."
    }
  ],
  "custom-priority-sort": [
    {
      "name": "JOIN to a priority-rank mapping CTE",
      "sql": "WITH priority_rank(priority, rank) AS (\n  SELECT 'high',   1\n  UNION ALL\n  SELECT 'medium', 2\n  UNION ALL\n  SELECT 'low',    3\n)\nSELECT t.title, t.priority\nFROM tasks t\nLEFT JOIN priority_rank pr ON t.priority = pr.priority\nORDER BY COALESCE(pr.rank, 3), t.created;",
      "explanation": "**Goal:** externalise the priority-to-rank mapping into a dedicated lookup table (a CTE), then JOIN tasks to it ÔÇö separating the \"what order?\" concern from the query logic.\n\n**Step 1 ÔÇö build the mapping CTE.** `priority_rank` is a tiny inline table built with `UNION ALL`. Each row pairs a label with its desired sort rank: highÔćĺ1, mediumÔćĺ2, lowÔćĺ3. This makes the ordering rules explicit and easy to extend without touching the main query.\n\n**Step 2 ÔÇö LEFT JOIN so no rows are lost.** A `LEFT JOIN` on `t.priority = pr.priority` attaches the matching rank to every task row. Tasks whose priority isn't in the CTE (e.g. `urgent`, `backlog`) find no match and receive `NULL` for `pr.rank`.\n\n**Step 3 ÔÇö COALESCE handles unknowns.** `COALESCE(pr.rank, 3)` maps any unmatched priority to rank 3, placing it in the same lowest bucket as `low` ÔÇö exactly mirroring the `ELSE 3` in the CASE approach.\n\n**Step 4 ÔÇö ORDER BY the joined rank.** `ORDER BY COALESCE(pr.rank, 3), t.created` produces the identical result as the CASE approach. The JOIN strategy is particularly useful when the mapping is large, needs to be reused across queries, or lives in a real database table instead of inline SQL."
    }
  ],
