      "explanation": "**Step 1 ÔÇö find IDs present in both tables.** `SELECT id FROM customers INTERSECT SELECT customer_id FROM orders` uses a set operation to produce exactly the customer IDs that appear in *both* the `customers` table and as `customer_id` values in `orders`. `INTERSECT` removes duplicates automatically, so even though orders contains customer 1 twice, the result is the distinct set {1, 3, 5}.\n\n**Step 2 ÔÇö look up the names.** `WHERE c.id IN (...)` filters the `customers` table to those IDs. Because we filter on `c.id` (the primary key) rather than on `name`, two customers who share the same name but have different IDs are each kept independently.\n\n**Step 3 ÔÇö result.** IDs 1, 3, 5 map to Ava, Cara, Eve ÔÇö the same three rows returned by the `EXISTS` and `IN` approaches, ordered by name."
