      "explanation": "An aggregation-based take: group each customer with their orders and keep only the groups that produced zero order rows.\n\n**Step 1 ÔÇö bring in all orders (or NULLs).** `LEFT JOIN orders o ON o.customer_id = c.id` fans out each customer to their matching order rows; customers with no orders get a single row with `o.id = NULL`.\n\n**Step 2 ÔÇö collapse per customer.** `GROUP BY c.id, c.name` collapses those rows into one group per customer. Grouping on `c.id` (the key) first ensures that two customers who happen to share a name are treated as separate groups.\n\n**Step 3 ÔÇö filter with HAVING.** `COUNT(o.id)` counts non-`NULL` values of `o.id` within each group. For customers with orders this count is Ôëą 1; for customers with no orders the `LEFT JOIN` produced only a `NULL` placeholder row, so `COUNT(o.id) = 0`. `HAVING COUNT(o.id) = 0` keeps only the zero-order groups.\n\n**Step 4 ÔÇö order.** `ORDER BY c.name` returns Ian, Kim. This strategy is useful when you simultaneously need other aggregates (e.g. total spend) alongside the \"no orders\" filter."
