      "explanation": "**Goal:** same computation, but use an inline subquery (derived table) instead of a CTE or a bare `ORDER BY` alias.\n\n**Step 1 ÔÇö write the inner subquery.** The parenthesised `SELECT` computes `ROUND(CAST(pages AS REAL) / price, 2) AS value` for every book, producing a two-column result set labelled `sub`. At this stage the rows are unordered.\n\n**Step 2 ÔÇö sort in the outer query.** The outer `SELECT title, value FROM (...) AS sub ORDER BY value DESC, title` treats `sub` like a regular table. Sorting here is equivalent to sorting from `books` directly, but the separation makes it explicit that the computed column `value` is already fully resolved before the sort happens.\n\n**CTE vs. derived table.** Both approaches wrap the computation, but a CTE is written *before* the main `SELECT` while a derived table is nested *inside* the `FROM` clause. Derived tables can be harder to read when deeply nested; CTEs scale better when the same sub-result is referenced multiple times. For a simple single-use case like this, both are equivalent."
