      "sql": "SELECT customer,\n       COUNT(*) FILTER (WHERE status = 'shipped') AS shipped,\n       COUNT(*) FILTER (WHERE status = 'pending') AS pending,\n       COUNT(*) FILTER (WHERE status = 'cancelled') AS cancelled\nFROM orders\nGROUP BY customer\nORDER BY customer;",
      "explanation": "1. The `FILTER (WHERE ...)` clause is SQL-standard syntax (supported in SQLite 3.30+) that restricts which rows an aggregate function sees, without needing a `CASE` expression inside it.\n2. `COUNT(*) FILTER (WHERE status = 'shipped')` counts only the rows in each group where `status = 'shipped'`; all other rows are invisible to that aggregate.\n3. When no rows in a group match the filter, `COUNT(*)` returns 0 ÔÇö so missing statuses appear as 0, not NULL, matching the desired output.\n4. One `COUNT(*) FILTER (...)` per status column produces the same pivot as the `CASE`-based approaches, but with cleaner, more declarative syntax.\n5. `ORDER BY customer` gives a stable total order."
