      "sql": "SELECT\n  (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM web_logins) + (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM app_logins) AS all_count,\n  (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM (SELECT user FROM web_logins UNION SELECT user FROM app_logins)) AS distinct_count;",
      "explanation": "1. `all_count` is computed without any set operation at all: since `UNION ALL` simply concatenates both tables, its row count is just the sum of the two table sizes ÔÇö `COUNT(*) FROM web_logins` + `COUNT(*) FROM app_logins` = 4 + 3 = 7.\n2. `distinct_count` still needs a `UNION` subquery (or `COUNT(DISTINCT)`) because deduplication must happen across both tables simultaneously.\n3. This approach highlights a key insight: the `UNION ALL` count is purely additive, so you don't need to materialise the combined set ÔÇö plain table counts suffice.\n4. The result is identical (7, 4), but the first column is computed through arithmetic rather than set-operation counting."
