      "name": "Cross join with subjects CTE + CASE",
      "sql": "WITH subjects(subject) AS (\n  SELECT 'english'\n  UNION ALL SELECT 'math'\n  UNION ALL SELECT 'science'\n)\nSELECT r.student,\n       s.subject,\n       CASE s.subject\n         WHEN 'math'    THEN r.math\n         WHEN 'science' THEN r.science\n         WHEN 'english' THEN r.english\n       END AS score\nFROM report r\nCROSS JOIN subjects s\nORDER BY r.student, s.subject;",
      "explanation": "1. A CTE called `subjects` acts as an inline lookup table holding the three subject labels as literal rows.\n2. `CROSS JOIN` pairs every student row with every subject row, producing 3 rows per student ÔÇö exactly the unpivot fan-out we need.\n3. The `CASE` expression inspects the current `subject` value and routes it to the matching score column from `report`, turning the wide column layout into a single `score` value per row.\n4. The `ORDER BY` at the end sorts the cross-product output by student then subject, matching the required order.\n\nThis strategy separates the *label enumeration* concern (CTE) from the *value extraction* concern (CASE), which scales cleanly if new subjects are added ÔÇö only the CTE and CASE need updating, not a new `UNION ALL` branch."
