      "explanation": "1. `json_object('english', r.english, 'math', r.math, 'science', r.science)` packs the three subject columns into a JSON object like `{\"english\":70,\"math\":90,\"science\":85}` ÔÇö one object per student row.\n2. `json_each(...)` is a SQLite table-valued function that expands a JSON object into rows, exposing a `key` column (the field name) and a `value` column (the field value). Joining it with a comma produces one row per key, fanning out the student row three times.\n3. Because `json_object` key order is insertion order, and we insert keys alphabetically (english, math, science), the `ORDER BY j.key` produces consistent alphabetical ordering that matches the oracle.\n4. This approach is the most idiomatic when the column list is known only at runtime or when you want to avoid repeating SELECT-per-column boilerplate."
