      "sql": "SELECT DISTINCT\n       student,\n       ROUND(\n         SUM(credits * grade_point) OVER (PARTITION BY student) /\n         SUM(credits)               OVER (PARTITION BY student),\n         2\n       ) AS gpa\nFROM enrollments\nORDER BY gpa DESC, student;",
      "explanation": "1. **`SUM(...) OVER (PARTITION BY student)`** computes a running total *within each student's partition* without collapsing the rows. Every row for Ada sees the same partition-level totals (`18.0` and `5`), so the ratio `18.0/5 = 3.6` is attached to every Ada row.\n2. **`DISTINCT`** then collapses all rows that share the same `(student, gpa)` pair ÔÇö turning the per-row window results into one row per student, exactly like a `GROUP BY` would, but after the window computation is done.\n3. **Why teach this approach:** it demonstrates that window functions can replicate group-level aggregates while keeping individual rows in scope. Here that extra per-row access isn't needed, but in queries that combine row-level detail with group-level totals in the same SELECT, this pattern (window + DISTINCT / outer GROUP BY) is the idiomatic SQLite solution."
